<br>
Dont let your child's schooling interfere with their education...<br>
<br>
I never felt it was only the responsibility of the schools to teach my kids. While they were young we spent many many family hours in museums (I love hands on science museums) , visiting forts, camping in the wilds, and wandering around the world as much as we could afford to.We played board games, card games, computer games, and I read to them each night til the youngest was 11 LOL. (Our last project was to read them Lord of the Rings, it took over a year including the Hobbit hehe).<br>
<br>
While they were young I ran my own business so I could be in the school one day a week and help. Being a computer geek I would take the kids in class to the lab and teach. But my true motivation here was to be a part of the school and able to make sure things were not going south in any huge way. I basically hand picked the school for my kids (they went out of district which if you read the education act in Canada can be done), and would make sure they had the best teacher available for each grade (funny how easy it is to influence this when you are seen as an asset to the school).  I never missed a parent teacher conference, or the opportunity to help out by going on field trip.  As a parent I always felt that I was part of the solution to making sure the school did the best job it could with my kids. <br>
<br>
I would not have homeschooled... I felt that the kids needed exposure to more than my own worldview.    <br>
<br>
I supplimented the kids experiences with summer camps at the local university, with making sure they got to go on any special events that were available (if you are Canadian look at the Shad Valley experience for you kid, cant speak highly enough of this one!)  <br>
<br>
Bottom line... there is no substitute for spending time with your kids ... for your kids if you want them to have a good education.  <br>
<br>
